AOC is quite popular within the NY 14th, but in an closed primary, turnout will be key. As we saw in 2016, people can quite easily become complacent. The longer lockdown NY experienced may encourage more people to get out to vote. The $2M that MCC raised is a shot across the bows, but it is highly unlikely to be enough. Best guess would be AOC 53%, MCC 39%.

Lowering my probability a bit of her winning a majority of the votes, as she has been doing a lot of TV commercials in the area, which makes me think that she has some real concerns about not winning the primary.

No polls to go off of. AOC won 57% of the vote in the 2018 primary. She has the incumbency advantage this time. However, she has a somewhat strong challenger in Caruso-Cabrera (https://www.politico.com/news/2020/04/09/chamber-commerce-aoc-primary-challenger-175917), and there are also two other challengers (unless they drop out before June 23). Intuitively, this would push her closer to 50% or even below 50%. I think there's little chance she loses outright, maybe a little under 10%. The question becomes whether this set of challengers takes more than 7% of the vote from her. With no polling yet, it's hard to say. I'll lean toward majority for now.

Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez (AOC) has the biggest profile among her primary challengers. According to Ballotpedia, she is the primary candidate with the most money (by a huge margin). According to Wikipedia, the 14th congressional district of NY has a Hispanic population of 49.80%. New York uses a closed primary process (where the selection of a party's candidates is limited to registered party members).
She is a strong incumbent, makes news frequently, and has established a donor base outside of her district.

The mere fact that despite the uphill battle, AOC was able to win the majority in 2018 against a popular incumbent candidate speaks volumes as to popular she was in the 14th district. Moreover, she has cultivated a huge presence on both the federal and international stage, marking her as an important figure in american and international politics. the importance of which is not lost on the voters of NY14. Finally, NY14 has already indicated that not only is it a deep blue district it is also progressive district and there is no progressive candidate that can challenge AOC and there just aren't enough moderate voters to win a majority, plus the challengers will likely just split the votes among themselves without touching AOC's solid base and its highly likely that some will drop out before the election, making a plurality even less likely than it already inconceivably is.

There are a lot of challengers, but, as far as I can tell, none who would cannibalise AOC's vote (i.e. challengers from the left), and if there were she'd have a very strong squeeze message. That said, the many horses in the race would perhaps leave a chance that she wouldn't have an outright majority (the last Primary being a two horse race as I understand it, though I'm not sure the previous incumbent was notably bad). Of course, I'll need to update this depending on how the campaigns seem to be shaking out.
